know what this page is all about without scrolling down or even without reading too much.","s":"Headers","u":"/docs/greetings","h":"#headers","p":16},{"i":23,"t":"You can configure the TOC heading levels either per-document or in the theme configuration. The headers are well-spaced so that the hierarchy is clear. lists will help you present the key points that you want your users to remember and you may nest them multiple times","s":"Only h2 and h3 will be in the TOC by default.","u":"/docs/greetings","h":"#only-h2-and-h3-will-be-in-the-toc-by-default","p":16},{"i":25,"t":"With {#custom-id} syntax you can set your own header id.","s":"Custom id headers","u":"/docs/greetings","h":"#custom-id","p":16},{"i":27,"t":"VPC Concepts Overview","s":"Overview","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/concepts","h":"","p":26},{"i":29,"t":"VPC Step-by-step instructions Overview","s":"Overview","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step","h":"","p":28},{"i":31,"t":"VPC Step-by-step instructions Manage connections","s":"Manage connections","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step/connections","h":"","p":30},{"i":33,"t":"caution You can't change the parameters of the connection after you create it. Perform the following steps to create a peer connection: Go to the console. In the list of services, select VPC. On the Connections tab, click Create connection. Specify the AWS account ID you want to connect to. Specify the AWS VPC ID. Provide your AWS IPv4 CIDR. You can also add a AWS IPv6 CIDR if you have such a range. Select your VPC Region and a zone within this region. Select your DoubleCloud Network to peer with. Click Create connection. Your connection is created, but you also need to enable it on the AWS side as shown in the next section: Open the AWS console. Go to the Peering connections section. Select your VPC peering connection and choose Actions → Accept Request. In the confirmation dialog, choose Yes, Accept.","s":"Create a connection","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step/connections","h":"#create-a-connection","p":30},{"i":35,"t":"Go to the console. In the list of services, select VPC. Switch to the Connections tab and select a connection to delete. Click and select Delete. See also: Concepts - Connections","s":"Delete a connection","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step/connections","h":"#modify-a-connection","p":30},{"i":37,"t":"Blog posts support Docusaurus Markdown features, such as MDX. tip Use the power of React to create interactive blog posts. <button onClick={() => alert('button clicked!')}>Click me!</button> Click me!","s":"MDX Blog Post","u":"/blog/mdx-blog-post","h":"","p":36},{"i":39,"t":"VPC Step-by-step instructions Manage virtual networks","s":"Manage virtual networks","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step/networks","h":"","p":38},{"i":41,"t":"Go to the console. In the list of services, select VPC. All the networks within your project are listed on the Networks tab. See also: Manage connections Concepts - Networks","s":"See the list of networks","u":"/docs/vpc-peering/step-by-step/networks","h":"#manage-networks","p":38}],"index":{"version":"2.3.9","fields":["t"],"fieldVectors":[["t/2",[0,3.242,1,3.612,2,3.242,3,3.242,4,3.242,5,2.479,6,2.479,7,2.479,8,2.479,9,2.479,10,2.479,11,2.479,12,2.479,13,2.479,14,2.479,15,2.479,16,2.479,17,2.479]],["t/4",[0,3.558,1,3.868,2,3.558,3,3.558,4,3.558,5,2.869,6,2.869,7,2.869,8,2.869,9,2.869,10,2.869,11,2.869,12,2.869,13,2.869,14,2.869,15,2.869,16,2.869,17,2.869,18,0.523,19,0.523,20,0.523,21,0.651,22,0.651,23,0.355,24,0.651,25,0.523,26,0.523,27,0.523,28,0.523,29,0.232,30,0.523]],["t/7",[31,1.13,32,2.922]],["t/9",[21,3.384,22,2.544,23,1.488,33,2.566,34,1.768,35,1.768,36,2.192,37,2.192,38,1.768,39,1.768,40,2.192,41,3.182,42,3.182,43,2.192,44,2.192,45,2.192,46,2.192,47,2.192,48,2.192,49,2.192,50,1.279,51,3.182,52,3.182,53,3.182,54,2.192,55,2.192,56,2.192,57,2.192,58,2.192,59,2.192,60,1.768,61,2.192,62,1.768,63,2.192,64,1.488,65,1.768,66,2.192,67,2.192]],["t/11",[31,1.091,68,2.108,69,4.153,70,2.108]],["t/13",[29,1.757,50,1